foia:ProcessedRequestSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of pending requests in beginning of fiscal year for the components is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: a request initially assigned to Office "A" in FY16 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a pending case for Office "A" at the end of FY16, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY17, the report will show Office "B" as the pending office at the start of FY16 rather than Office "A".

The Department reported 508 requests pending FY16 but in FY17 one of the requests pending FY16 was deleted because it was mistakenly entered in FY16. As a result, report is showing now 507 requests pending for FY16.

foia:ProcessedAppealSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of pending appeals in beginning of fiscal year for the components is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: an appeal initially assigned to Office "A" in FY16 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a pending appeal for Office "A" at the end of FY16, but when Office "B" closes the appeal in FY17, the report will show Office "B" as the pending office for FY16 rather than Office "A".

foia:PersonnelAndCostSection.foia:FootnoteText: M represents Multiple Offices assigned, therefore their personnel are captured under the individual offices data.

foia:FeesCollectedSection.foia:FootnoteText: Agency total Fees Collected reflects amount collected in FY17. This includes fees collected from prior year, closed cases.

foia:ProcessedRequestComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: The Department reported 2,445 requests received for FY16 but in FY17 one of the requests received for FY16 was deleted because it was mistakenly entered in FY16. As a result, report is showing 2,444 requests received for FY16.

The discrepancy in the number of requests in beginning of fiscal year for the components is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: a request initially assigned to Office "A" in FY16 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a request for Office "A" at the end of FY16, but when Office "B" closes the request in FY17, the report will show Office "B" as the office at the start of FY16 rather than Office "A".

foia:BackloggedRequestComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of backlog requests pending FY16 is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: a request received initially to Office "A" in FY16 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a backlog for Office "A" at the end of FY16, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY17, the report will show Office "B" as the backlog office at the start of FY17 rather than Office "A."

foia:ProcessedAppealComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of received appeals in beginning of fiscal year for the components is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: a request initially assigned to Office "A" in FY16 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a received appeal for Office "A" at the end of FY16, but when Office "B" closes the appeal in FY17, the report will show Office "B" as the received office at the start of FY16 rather than Office "A".

foia:BackloggedAppealComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of backlog appeals pending FY16 is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: an appeal received initially to Office "A" in FY16 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a backlog for Office "A" at the end of FY16, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY17, the report will show Office "B" as the backlog office at the start of FY17 rather than Office "A."
